Here's a modern MSTest approach using `MockHttpMessageHandler`, async test methods, and cancellation testing:

```csharp
[TestClass]
public class DataFetcherTests
{
    [TestMethod]
    public async Task FetchAsync_ReturnsContent_OnSuccess()
    {
        var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("hello", HttpStatusCode.OK);
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

        var result = await fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com");

        Assert.AreEqual("hello", result);
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public async Task FetchAsync_Throws_OnNonSuccessStatus()
    {
        var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("", HttpStatusCode.NotFound);
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

        await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<HttpRequestException>(
            () => fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com"));
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public async Task FetchAsync_Throws_WhenCancelled()
    {
        var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("ok", HttpStatusCode.OK);
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        cts.Cancel();

        await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<TaskCanceledException>(
            () => fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com", cts.Token));
    }

    // Reusable fake handler — no external mocking library needed
    private sealed class MockHttpMessageHandler(
        string content, HttpStatusCode status) : HttpMessageHandler
    {
        protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
            HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
        {
            cancellationToken.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            return Task.FromResult(new HttpResponseMessage(status)
            {
                Content = new StringContent(content)
            });
        }
    }
}
```

**Key patterns used:**

- **`async Task` test methods** — MSTest natively awaits them; never use `async void`.
- **`Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync`** — MSTest v4's preferred API for asserting a specific exception type (replaces `ThrowsExceptionAsync` which also matched subtypes).
- **Cancellation testing** — pre-cancel a `CancellationTokenSource` and verify `TaskCanceledException` is thrown.
- **No mocking framework needed** — a custom `HttpMessageHandler` gives full control over responses without Moq/NSubstitute overhead.
- **`[TestMethod][Timeout(5000)]`** — add this attribute if you want a per-test safety net against hangs (value in ms). MSTest also supports `[AssemblyInitialize]`-level timeouts.
